8.  The specific duties follow: 

(i)  Investigate and analyze existing systems and procedures for land administration 
in Uzbekistan; 
(ii)  Propose a general design of information models, cadastral and land registration 
procedures, land use and environmental monitoring and the legislative support 
for an integrated land administration system; 
(iii)  Develop a proposal for changes in legislation to improve tenure security for 
private  farmers  and  for  more  efficient  computer-supported  procedures  for 
cadastral and land registration; 
(iv)  Procure hardware and software for the test system; 
(v)  Engage domestic consultants; 
(vi)  Advise on the design of a land information center in Syrdarja Province; 
(vii)  Develop  a  training  program  and  plan  training  for  staff  at  the  regional  land 
information center; 
(viii)  Actively participate in on-the-job-training of counterpart staff, in training courses, 
and in transfer of experiences and knowledge; 
(ix)  Lead the task force in planning and implementing the pilot test; 
(x)  Actively  participate  in  evaluating  the  pilot  test  and  drafting  legislation  for 
improved procedures and land tenure; 
(xi)  Organize workshops and regional seminar; 
(xii)  Assist the TA manager in the managing and administering the TA; 
(xiii)  Be  responsible  for  quality  assurance  of  the  consultancy  input  and  the 
consultant’s reporting; and 
(xiv)  Prepare and submit inception, progress, and final reports. 

2.  Cadastral Survey and Mapping Expert (1.5 person-months) 

9.  The  cadastral  survey  and  mapping  expert  will  advise  on  developing  an  efficient 
methodology for cadastral surveying and mapping of rural land, and how these surveys can be 
integrated with surveys of other areas. The expert will also advise on developing standards and 
procuring equipment, and will participate in training activities. The expert will have a university 
degree in land surveying, geodesy, photogrammetry or cartography, with more than 10 years 
work with cadastral surveying within a professional cadastral survey organization. Experience in 
the following areas will be particularly desirable: (i) development of cadastral methodology 
including modern surveying, digital map construction, and establishment of cadastral databases 
for  land  registration  purposes;  (ii)  development  of  geographic  information  system  (GIS) 
applications  from  cadastral  databases;  and  (iii)  working  experiences  in  transitional  and 
developing countries in a similar field. A working knowledge of Russian is desirable. 

10.  The specific duties will include the following: 

(i)  Investigate  and  analyze  the  existing  capacity  for  cadastral  surveys  within 
GosKomZem; 
(ii)  Analyze  the  existing  system  for  graphic  information  developed  within  the 
Technical Assistance for Commonwealth Independent States (TACIS) program 
by UzGeodesCadastre and its usefulness for continued development; 
(iii)  Investigate existing standards, regulations and manuals for cadastral survey, and 
analyze their suitability for efficient cadastral surveying for digital land information 
systems;
